</div></div>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Hanging-Leg-Raise">Hanging Leg Raise</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/hanging-leg-raise" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">hanging leg raise</a> is a more advanced bodyweight core exercise best suited for intermediate to advanced lifters. Lifters are required to be able to hold onto a bar while executing the hanging leg raise movement pattern. In the exercise, the glutes, obliques, rectus abdominis, hip flexors, and more muscle groups are activated.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Adding the hanging leg raise to your workouts will actively <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25111163/#:~:text=The%20hanging%20straight%20leg%20raise%20created%20the%20highest%20challenge%20to%20the%20abdominal%20wall%20(%3E130%25%20MVC%20in%20rectus%20abdominis%2C%2088%25%20MVC%20in%20external%20oblique)." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">target the rectus abdominis</a> and external obliques, helping strengthen them. Preserving strength in the core is critical for <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2411-5142/7/3/67#:~:text=The%20importance%20of%20abdominal%20muscle%20strength%20is%20well%20recognized%20for%20the%20prevention%20of%20lower%20back%20disorders%20and%20the%20proper%20execution%20of%20occupational%20and%20athletic%20activities%2C%20and%20for%20this%20reason%20special%20exercises%20are%20used%20for%20its%20development%20%5B1%2C2%2C3%2C4%2C5%5D." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">deterring lower back disorders</a> and aiding performance in occupational and athletic activities.&nbsp;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Hanging Leg Raises" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980279132?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Hanging Leg Raise Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Find an available pull-up bar at your gym or assemble a mounted one in your home.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Stand underneath the bar.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Use a box or bench to reach the bar.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Grip the bar in an overhand grip.</li>



<li>Move off the bench, allowing the arms to straighten and the body to hang. This is your starting position.</li>



<li>Inhale.</li>



<li>Exhale and lift the legs in front of you until they are parallel to the floor.</li>



<li>Pause.</li>



<li>Inhale and return to the starting position.</li>



<li>Repeat for goal-driven sets and reps.&nbsp;</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Avoid swaying or swinging, as this can detract from desired muscle activation. Activate the glutes and abdominal muscles to keep the body tight and controlled.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Refrain from using momentum to drive the legs up during repetitions, as this is considered cheating. Prioritize slow and controlled movement to increase muscle engagement.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



